Introduction

The 70-kDa heat shock proteins (Hsp70s) constitute the central hub of the cellular protein quality surveillance network, assisting numerous protein-folding processes and cooperating with all major cellular chaperone systems ( Mayer and Bukau, 2005 ). Processes involving Hsp70s include folding of newly synthesized polypeptides and their trafficking across membranes; prevention of protein aggregation, solubilization of protein aggregates, and their subsequent refolding; assembly and disassembly of oligomeric protein structures; control of activity of many regulatory proteins; and protein degradation by the proteasome and autophagy ( Kettern et al., 2010 , Meimaridou et al., 2009 ). Not surprisingly, Hsp70s are linked to numerous diseases, notably cancer, neurodegeneration, and infections ( Calderwood et al., 2006 , Fontaine et al., 2016 , Ghazaei, 2017 , Mayer, 2005 , Radons, 2016 , Shonhai et al., 2011 ), and in recent years became a target for drug development ( Zuiderweg et al., 2017 ).

The enormous versatility of Hsp70 chaperones relies on the transient interaction of their C-terminal substrate polypeptide-binding domain (SBD) with a short degenerative sequence motif found frequently in virtually all proteins ( Rüdiger et al., 1997 ). This interaction is regulated through an intricate allosteric mechanism between their N-terminal nucleotide-binding domain (NBD) and their SBD, resulting in ultrahigh affinity through a non-equilibrium binding mode ( De Los Rios and Barducci, 2014 , Mayer and Kityk, 2015 , Zuiderweg et al., 2013 ). In the ATP-bound state, affinity for polypeptides is low but peptide association and dissociation rates are high. Upon ATP hydrolysis , affinity of polypeptides is increased 10- to 50-fold, while peptide association and dissociation rates are decreased 100- and more than 1,000-fold, respectively ( Figure 1 A). The structures of the ATP- and ADP-bound conformations rationalized these differences ( Figure 1 B). Ultrahigh affinity is achieved when polypeptides associate with high rates to the ATP-bound state and concomitant ATP hydrolysis traps the substrate protein by transition to the ADP-bound state with low substrate dissociation rates. However, the intrinsic ATP hydrolysis rate of Hsp70 is very low and requires timely stimulation by the substrate itself in synergism with J-domain proteins (JDPs) ( Karzai and McMacken, 1996 , Laufen et al., 1999 ). Although Hsp70s are paradigm chaperones, in the absence of JDPs, they generally fail in the most basic chaperone function: the prevention of protein aggregation. Thus, efficient interaction of Hsp70s with substrates depends entirely on JDP co-chaperones, which act as targeting factors for Hsp70s.

    Download : Download high-res image (900KB)
    Download : Download full-size image 

Figure 1 . Crystal Structure of DnaK·ATP in Complex with the J-Domain of DnaJ

(A) JDPs in synergism with substrates stimulate the ATPase activity of Hsp70 proteins, leading to efficient substrate trapping.

(B) Structure of Hsp70·ATP (PDB: 4B9Q ) and Hsp70·ADP (PDB: 2KHO ) with bound substrate (dark blue spheres).

(C) Structure of DnaK in complex with ATP·Mg 2+ and the J-domain of DnaJ. NBD in dark teal (lobe I) and cyan (lobe II), linker in yellow, SBDβ in dark red, SBDα in orange, the J-domain in purple (PDB: 5NRO ), and the HPD motif in green spheres.

The number of JDPs present in each cell has increased tremendously in the course of evolution ( Kampinga and Craig, 2010 ). JDPs are multi-domain proteins that are divided in three classes according to their domain composition. All JDPs contain the name-giving J-domain, a helical hairpin structure of 70–75 residues, which is at the N terminus of class A and class B JDPs but can be anywhere in class C proteins . Class A JDPs share all domains of the prototypic Escherichia coli DnaJ: the N-terminal J-domain is followed by a glycine/phenylalanine (G/F)-rich flexible region of ∼30 residues, two homologous β sandwich domains, with a Zn 2+ -finger domain inserted into the first of the two, and a C-terminal dimerization domain. Class B JDPs contain all domains of class A proteins except for the Zn 2+ finger. Class C JDPs only have the J-domain in common and can have a wide variety of other domains or functional motifs. Class A and class B JDPs are considered general co-chaperones that interact with unfolded, misfolded, or aggregated proteins and transfer them to Hsp70. Class C proteins are believed to be more specific for a small subset of substrates or are located at places like the ribosomal exit tunnel or translocation pores where polypeptides emerge to be bound by Hsp70. Genetic and biochemical data demonstrated that the J-domain is necessary and sufficient for functional interaction with Hsp70s ( Karzai and McMacken, 1996 , Wall et al., 1994 ). Therefore, the J-domain-Hsp70 interaction is at the heart of the multitude of functions of Hsp70 systems.

Here, we present the crystal structure of the J-domain of E. coli DnaJ in complex with the ATP-bound open conformation of the E. coli Hsp70 DnaK. Our structure reveals the molecular mechanism for the synergistic action of J-domain and substrate in stimulating the ATPase activity of Hsp70 and trapping substrates.
Results
Overcoming the Constrains of Transient J-Domain-Hsp70 Interactions

To overcome the main obstacle to structural investigations of the J-domain-Hsp70 interaction, the transient nature of this interaction, we fused the first 105 amino acids of DnaJ, comprising the J-domain and the G/F-rich region, via a three-residue linker to the N terminus of DnaK (further referred to as JD-DnaK) ( Figure S1 A). The unstructured 33-residue G/F-rich region ( Szyperski et al., 1994 ) bridges more than 100 Å and allows the J-domain to reach any position in DnaK, since in the ATP-bound conformation, no part of DnaK is more than 60 Å away from its N terminus ( Kityk et al., 2012 ). Furthermore, the J-domain and G/F-rich region are sufficient to replace full-length DnaJ and its close homolog, CbpA, in E. coli , allowing the ΔdnaJ ΔcbpA strain to grow at 14.5°C and 39.5°C ( Kelley and Georgopoulos, 1997 ), downregulate the heat shock response ( Wall et al., 1995 ), and support bacteriophage λ replication ( Wall et al., 1994 ). The J-domain in the chimeric protein stimulated ATPase activity 20 times more efficiently than equimolar concentrations of DnaJ(1–105) stimulate DnaKwt when added in trans , consistent with the expectation that the fusion construct provides J-domain function at a much higher local concentration ( Figures S1 B and S1C). Thus, the J-domain of JD-DnaK functionally interacts with the Hsp70 part of the fusion construct. Of note, full-length DnaJ, added at the high concentrations used in our quenched-flow single-turnover ATPase assays (10 μM), was able to stimulate DnaKwt to ATPase rates similar to those as observed for our JD-DnaK construct. Because full-length DnaJ is known to mimic a substrate in the absence of other protein substrates, thereby providing the J-domain and a substrate signal for ATP hydrolysis ( Laufen et al., 1999 ), our construct also might provide J-domain and substrate function, presumably through the G/F-rich linker.

For crystallization, we introduced three additional modifications into JD-DnaK to stabilize the ATP state of the protein. First, we replaced Thr199 (DnaK numbering throughout) with alanine , which abrogates ATPase activity without affecting the allosteric mechanism ( Barthel et al., 2001 ) ( Figure S1 A). Second, we covalently fixed the α-helical lid of the SBD (SBDα) to the NBD via a disulfide bridge formed between cysteines introduced at positions 47 and 529, which stabilizes the physiologically relevant open conformation of DnaK ( Kityk et al., 2012 ). Third, we replaced the last 30 residues of DnaK, known to be unstructured ( Zhu et al., 1996 ), by 5  histidine residues. This construct, DnaJ(1–105)-DnaK(2–606)-E47C,T199A,F529C-H 5 (short JD-DnaK cryst ), was oxidized to form a disulfide bridge and crystallized.
Overall Structure of the J-Domain-DnaK Complex

Phases were obtained by molecular replacement using the structure of full-length DnaK ( Kityk et al., 2012 ), residues 3–65 of the J-domain were built manually, and the complex refined at 3.25 Å resolution ( Table 1 ). The J-domain (3–65) and DnaK (2–604) are well defined in the electron density, whereas no electron density was observed for the G/F region ( Figures 1 C and S1 D). The structure of DnaK in the JD-DnaK cryst construct closely resembles the structure of DnaK·ATP solved previously ( Kityk et al., 2012 , Qi et al., 2013 ) with small changes close to the bound J-domain ( Figures 2 A and 2B). The DnaK part consists of the NBD in complex with Mg 2+ -ATP and the SBD in the open conformation with α-helical lid (SBDα) and β sandwich domain (SBDβ) separated from each other and docked onto the NBD. The highly conserved interdomain linker, which is important for ATP hydrolysis ( Vogel et al., 2006b ), is inserted into the lower crevice of the NBD. The J-domain consists of four α helices (I–IV) and is similar to the nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) structures of DnaJ’s J-domain ( Figure 2 C). The J-domain binds to DnaK at the interface formed between NBD and SBDβ ( Figure 1 C), and contacts formed between J-domain and DnaK, covering an interface area of 923 Å 2 , are fully consistent with genetic, biochemical, and structural data available ( Figures 2 D and 2E), including a recent molecular modeling study ( Malinverni et al., 2017 ).

