Figure 2 . The Structure of JD-DnaK cryst Overlays Well with Previous Structures of DnaK·ATP and Is Completely Consistent with Previous Genetic, Biochemical, and Biophysical Data

The structure of JD-DnaK cryst aligns well with the structure of DnaK·ATP in the absence of a J-domain (PDB: 4B9Q ; Kityk et al., 2012 ; with a root-mean-square deviation [RSMD] = 0.323 over 430 atoms) (PDB: 4JN4 ; Qi et al., 2013 ; RMSD = 0.382 over 442 atoms).

(A) Ribbon representation of an overlay of the NBD plus linker of JD-DnaK cryst (brown, red, yellow) with the NBD plus linker of DnaK·ATP (blue, PDB: 4B9Q ; Kityk et al., 2012 ). Arrowheads point to small deviations within the structure most likely caused by direct contact with the J-domain.

(B) Ribbon representation of an overlay of the linker plus SBD of JD-DnaK cryst (yellow, dark red, and orange) with the linker plus SBD of DnaK·ATP (blue, PDB: 4B9Q ; Kityk et al., 2012 ).

(C) Cartoon representation of an overlay of the J-domain of JD-DnaK cryst (purple) with the NMR structure of the J-domain of E. coli DnaJ (green, PDB: 1XBL ; Pellecchia et al., 1996 ). The HPD motifs of both structures are shown as sticks. The helices of the J-domain are numbered (JαI–JαIV).

(D) Residues of the J-domain contacting DnaK are consistent with previous genetic, biochemical, and structural data. Top: J-domain colored according chemical shift perturbations found in nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) experiments by titrating the NBD of DnaK to 13 C- 15 N-labeled J-domain (magenta and red; Greene et al., 1998 ) and according to intensity quenching observed in NMR paramagnetic relaxation enhancement experiments (red and orange residues are within 5–15 Å of position 210 in DnaK; Ahmad et al., 2011 ). Middle: J-domain colored according to possible polar (<3.5 Å) and non-polar contacts (<4 Å) in our structure. Bottom: J-domain with residues colored according to growth defects observed in E. coli upon replacement by alanine or glycine ( Genevaux et al., 2002 ).

(E) Surface representation of the NBD (residues 2–385) plus linker (residues 386–393; lavender) colored according to mutagenesis (magenta and red; Gässler et al., 1998 ) and NMR experiments (red and orange residues are within 5–15 Å of position 30 in the J-domain; Ahmad et al., 2011 ). The J-domain is shown in cartoon representation for orientation.
Interactions of the J-Domain with the NBD and the Universally Conserved Linker

The universally conserved HPD motif (His33-Pro34-Asp35), which is essential for stimulation of the ATPase activity in all J-domain/Hsp70 pairs tested so far ( Campbell et al., 1997 , Kelley and Georgopoulos, 1997 , Tsai and Douglas, 1996 , Wall et al., 1994 ), protrudes toward the interdomain linker of DnaK ( Figure 1 C). His33 JD , Tyr25 JD , and Met30 JD form hydrophobic contacts with the linker residues Leu390 DnaK and Leu392 DnaK ( Figure 3 A). In addition, His33 JD /NE2 is at hydrogen-bond distance to the backbone carbonyl of Leu391 DnaK , Arg36 JD /NH1 and NH2 form polar contacts with the backbone carbonyls of Lys387 DnaK and Val389 DnaK ( Figure 3 B), and Asp35 JD /OD2 interacts with Arg167 DnaK /NH1. Notably, Arg167 DnaK , Leu390 DnaK , and Leu392 DnaK were previously suggested to be involved in DnaK-DnaJ interactions and Leu391 DnaK in allostery in DnaK ( Kumar et al., 2011 , Laufen et al., 1999 , Mayer et al., 1999 , Suh et al., 1998 ), and Tyr25 JD and Arg36 JD are important for DnaJ function in vivo ( Genevaux et al., 2002 ). Additionally, Asp35 JD /OD2 interacts with Gln378 DnaK /NE2 in the NBD. Gln378 had not been implicated in DnaK-DnaJ interactions before. Thus, we replaced Gln378 DnaK with alanine and determined the efficiency of DnaJ and a substrate to stimulate the ATPase activity of the mutant protein . At the concentrations employed, the low basal ATPase rate of DnaKwt (0.0007 s −1 ) was stimulated 11.7-fold by DnaJ, 3.7-fold by the physiological substrate heat shock transcription factor σ 32 , and 23-fold in the presence of both ( Figure 3 C). The basal ATPase activity of DnaK-Q378A was stimulated 2.9-fold by σ 32 but only 3-fold by DnaJ and 5-fold when both co-factors were added, suggesting that Gln378 DnaK is important for the interaction with DnaJ. Moreover, DnaK-Q378A was less efficient than DnaKwt in refolding chemically denatured luciferase in vitro ( Figure 3 D) and supported growth of a Δ dnaK strain at 40°C less well when expressed a equal levels ( Figures 3 E and S2 ), suggesting that Gln378 DnaK is important for DnaK’s chaperone activity in vitro and in vivo .

