Figure 3 . The Universally Conserved HPD Motif Has a Functional Role in the Stimulation of ATP Hydrolysis by DnaK

(A) Zoom into the JD-DnaK cryst structure, highlighting hydrophobic interactions. Indicated residues in space-filling representation in atom colors with carbon in black (linker), purple (J-domain), green (HPD-motif), and dark red (SBDβ).

(B) Zoom into the JD-DnaK cryst structure, highlighting polar interactions of HPD motif His33 and Asp35 and Arg36 of the J-doman with linker, NBD and SBDβ. Residues colored in atom colors with carbon in dark teal (NBD lobe I), black (linker), purple (J-domain), green (HPD-motif), and dark red (SBDβ). Black dashed lines, potential hydrogen bonds (distance 2.2–3.4 Å).

(C) Single-turnover ATPase rate of DnaKwt and DnaK-Q378A in the absence of cofactors and in the presence of DnaJ (50 nM), σ 32 (1 μM), or both (mean ± SEM, n = 3).

(D) Refolding of chemically denatured luciferase in the absence of chaperones (black) and in the presence of DnaKwt (dark blue) or DnaK-Q378A (dark red; 800 nM), DnaJ (40 nM), and GrpE (400 nM) (mean ± SEM, n = 3).

(E) Complementation of the temperature-sensitivity phenotype of a Δ dnaK E. coli strain. Tenfold serial dilutions of an overnight culture of a Δ dnaK strain containing an empty vector or expressing dnaKwt or Q378A were grown at 30°C or 40°C (for protein levels, see Figure S2 ).
Interactions of the J-Domain with the SBD Coordinates Substrate Signal

Two polar/electrostatic and hydrophobic contact interfaces between the J-domain and DnaK ensure correct positioning of the J-domain at the NBD-SBD interface of DnaK ( Figure S3 ). The first interface is formed between helix II of the J-domain and lobe II of the NBD, involving Arg22 JD /NH2-Glu206 DnaK /OE1, Arg22 JD /NH2-Glu217 DnaK /OE1, Lys26 JD /NZ-Glu217 DnaK /OE1, and Arg27 JD /NH2-Asp211 DnaK /OD2 ( Figure 4 A). These residues were implicated previously in DnaK-DnaJ interactions ( Ahmad et al., 2011 , Gässler et al., 1998 ). The second contact interface is formed between the HPD motif and helix III of the J-domain and the SBDβ of DnaK. This interface involves two polar contacts, Lys48 JD /NZ-Asp477 DnaK /OD1 and Lys51 JD /NZ-Thr420 DnaK /OG1, and two hydrophobic contacts, Pro34 JD -Pro419 DnaK and Phe47 JD -Pro419 DnaK ( Figures 3 A, 3B, and 4 B). To our knowledge, such an interaction has never been suggested before. However, Pro34 JD and Phe47 JD were shown to be important in vivo ( Genevaux et al., 2002 ), and replacement of Pro419 DnaK influences substrate binding ( Burkholder et al., 1996 ). We analyzed the importance of the remaining contacts for DnaK functions in vivo . In contrast to DnaK-T420A, DnaK-D477A was not able to complement the temperature-sensitivity phenotype of the ΔdnaK strain when expressed at equal levels ( Figures 4 C and S2 ). Consistently, a ΔdnaJ ΔcbpA strain harboring DnaJ-K48A or DnaJ-K48E exhibited growth defects at 40°C ( Figure S4 A). These data suggest that the Asp477 DnaK -Lys48 JD contact, but not the Thr420 DnaK -Lys51 JD contact, is critical for the DnaK-DnaJ system in vivo . Of note, Lys51 JD /NZ may also form contacts with Glu55 JD /OE1 and OE2, which may weaken the Thr420 DnaK -Lys51 JD contact, suggesting a reason why its contribution to the J-domain/DnaK interaction is small. However, the mutant J-domain (DnaJ(1–75)-K51A) stimulated ATPase activity of wild-type DnaK in synergism with a substrate peptide, comprising the DnaK recognition sequence within σ 32 ( Rodriguez et al., 2008 ), less efficiently than the wild-type J-domain of DnaJ ( Figure S4 B), suggesting that Lys51 JD nevertheless contributes to the interaction with DnaK. In contrast, DnaJ(1–75)-K48A did not significantly stimulate ATPase activity under these conditions compared with stimulation of the peptide alone, indicating that the Lys48 JD -Asp477 DnaK interaction is much more important. Similarly, the replacement of Lys26 and Arg36 of DnaJ(1–75), two other sites with polar contacts with DnaK (see above), with alanine also compromised J-domain function in single-turnover ATPase assays, indicating that these contacts are also much more important for the J-domain DnaK interaction than the Lys51 JD -Thr420 DnaK interaction ( Figure S4 B).

    Download : Download high-res image (931KB)
