Figure 4 . The J-Domain Enhances Substrate-Mediated Signal for ATP Hydrolysis

(A and B) Zoom into the JD-DnaK cryst structure, highlighting the contacts of the J-domain with the NBD (A) and the SBDβ (B). See also Figure S3 .

(C) Complementation of the temperature sensitivity of a Δ dnaK E. coli strain. Tenfold serial dilutions of an overnight culture of a Δ dnaK strain containing an empty vector or expressing dnaKwt , dnaK -T420A, or dnaK -D477A were grown at 30°C or 40°C (for protein levels, see Figure S4 ).

(D) Refolding of chemically denatured luciferase in the absence of chaperones (black) and the presence of DnaKwt (dark blue) or DnaK-D477A (dark red; 800 nM), DnaJ (40 nM), and GrpE (400 nM) (mean ± SEM, n = 3; data for DnaKwt and no chaperones are the same as in Figure 2 D).

(E) Single-turnover ATPase rates of DnaKwt and DnaK-D477A in the absence of cofactors and in the presence of DnaJ (50 nM), σ 32 (1 μM), or both (mean ± SEM, n = 3).

(F) DnaK-D477A has a lower affinity for substrates. Equilibrium titration of the fluorescent-labeled peptide σ 32 -Q132-Q144-C-IAANS ( Mayer et al., 2000 ) with DnaKwt and DnaK-D477A. Inset, K D values (mean ± SEM, n = 3; ∗∗∗∗ p < 0.0001; determined by F-test).

(G) Single-turnover ATPase rates of DnaKwt, DnaK-M404A ( Mayer et al., 2000 ), or DnaK-D477A in the presence of DnaJwt or DnaJ-K48A (20 nM) and increasing concentrations of σ 32 (mean ± SEM, n = 3).

In vitro , DnaK-D477A refolded chemically denatured luciferase less efficiently than DnaKwt ( Figure 4 D). Individually, DnaJ and σ 32 stimulated the ATPase activity of DnaK-D477A only 1.7-fold and together 5.3-fold, which is significantly lower than the stimulation of DnaKwt ( Figure 4 E). The decreased stimulation of DnaK-D477A’s ATPase activity by σ 32 relative to DnaKwt was unexpected, because Asp477 is more than 15 Å away from the substrate-binding cleft. Indeed, affinity measurements revealed that DnaK-D477A has a 2.3-fold lower affinity for the substrate than DnaKwt ( Figure 4 F). However, the reduced affinity of DnaK-D477A for substrates was not responsible for the reduced synergistic stimulation of its ATPase activity. We compared the ATPase activity of DnaK-D477A in the presence of 20 nM DnaJ and increasing concentrations of σ 32 with the ATPase activity of DnaKwt and DnaK-M404A, a DnaK variant with an affinity for substrates comparable to DnaK-D477A ( Mayer et al., 2000 ). Despite a 2.8-fold lower affinity for substrates, DnaK-M404A’s ATPase activity was as responsive to stimulation with increasing concentrations of σ 32 in the presence of DnaJ as DnaKwt’s ATPase activity ( Figure 4 G). In contrast, the ATPase activity of DnaK-D477A was stimulated much less efficiently, suggesting that Asp477 is indeed required for efficient synergistic stimulation of ATPase activity by DnaJ and a substrate.

The backbone amide and carbonyl of Asp477 form hydrogen bonds with the amide and carbonyl of His485, which is contiguous to Leu484, a residue previously demonstrated to be an essential part of the signal transduction pathway from the substrate to the catalytic center for ATP hydrolysis ( Kityk et al., 2015 ). Consistently, increasing concentrations of σ 32 also stimulated the ATP hydrolysis rate of DnaKwt less efficiently in the presence of DnaJ-K48A than in the presence of DnaJwt, demonstrating that disruption of the Lys48 JD -Asp477 DnaK interaction handicaps signal transduction from the substrate to the catalytic center in DnaKwt.
Residues Involved in the J-domain-Hsp70 Interaction Are Evolutionarily Conserved

To answer the question whether the J-domain-Hsp70 interface is conserved in evolution we performed blast searches in combination with multiple sequence alignments . We used E. coli DnaJ, Saccharomyces cerevisiae Ydj1, and human DnaJA1 (Hdj2), as examples for class A JDPs, E. coli CbpA, S. cerevisiae Sis1, and human DnaJB1 (Hdj1) as examples of class B JDPs in a BLAST query against the UNIPROT90 (DnaJ, Ydj1, CbpA, and Sis1) database of clusters of 90% mutually identical protein sequences or against the database of vertebrate protein sequences (DnaJA1 and DnaJB1) on the European Molecular Biology Laboratory (EMBL) EBI server. We retrieved 200 sequences for each query and performed a Clustal Ω alignment. After removal of incomplete sequences, we retained 200 (DnaJ), 198 (Ydj1), 187 (DnaJA1), 189 (CbpA), 200 (Sis1), and 183 (DnaJB1) sequences and analyzed the conservation of the residues indicated. Except for Lys51 JD , which is not essential, all sites involved in the interaction of the J-domain with DnaK are conserved in JDPs from bacteria to humans ( Figure 5 , top). Similarly, the sequences of E. coli DnaK, S. cerevisiae Ssa1, and human Hsc70 were used as query against the UNIPROT90 and vertebrate database and the retrieved sequences (200 each) used in Clustal Ω alignments ( Figure 5 A, bottom). These alignments suggest that all J-domains interact with Hsp70s in a similar way. To test this hypothesis, we replaced Glu218, Gln376, and Asp479 in human Hsc70 (corresponding to Glu217, Gln378, and Asp477 in E. coli DnaK) with alanine and determined the single-turnover ATPase rates of wild-type and mutant proteins in the absence and presence of the human JDP Hdj1 ( Figure 5 B). Whereas the replacement of these residues in human Hsc70 did not affect basal ATPase activity, stimulation of ATPase activity by Hdj1 was significantly lower, demonstrating that these residues are also important for functional interaction of the J-domain of human Hdj1 with human Hsc70.

    Download : Download high-res image (689KB)
    Download : Download full-size image 

Figure 5 . Residues Involved in J-Domain-Hsp70 Interactions Are Conserved in Evolution

(A) Top: relative identity (same residue as in E. coli DnaJ, indicated below the columns; darker colors) or similarity (as indicated in parenthesis below the columns; lighter colors) as derived by a BLAST search using class A JDPs E. coli DnaJ, S. cerevisiae Ydj1 and human DnaJA1, and class B JDPs E. coli CbpA, S. cerevisiae Sis1, and human DnaJB1 as query against the UNIPROT90 and vertebrate databases and subsequent Clustal Ω sequence alignment . Bottom: same as in the top panel, except that the sequences of E. coli DnaK, S. cerevisiae Ssa1, and human Hsc70 were used as a query. The arrows between the two panels connect the pairs of residues that interact with each other. The brackets indicate polar interaction with the backbone carbonyl or amide proton. Of note, because of a short (4-residue) deletion in eukaryotic Hsp70s corresponding to residues 211–214 of DnaK, the Clustal Ω sequence alignment does not detect homologs of residues 206 and 211, which in our structure interact with Arg22 JD and Arg27 JD .

(B) Single-turnover ATPase rates of wild-type and mutant human Hsc70 (HSPA8) in the absence and presence of human Hdj1 (DNAJB1, 2 μM) (mean ± SD, n = 3; ∗∗∗∗ p < 0.0001; ∗∗∗ p = 0.0001, ANOVA Sidak’s multiple comparisons test).

In addition, we performed an alignment using all Hsp70 sequences found in the genomes of E. coli , S. cerevisiae , and Homo sapiens , including the more distant relatives. Most sites in DnaK contacted by the J-domain are conserved in canonical Hsp70 proteins, but not in Hsp70 homologs that do not interact with JDPs, as the Hsp110s and Hsp70 components of the ribosome-associated complex ( Figure S5 ). We also performed a similar alignment of all JDPs of E. coli , S. cerevisiae , and the class A and class B JDPs of humans. These alignments show some deviations between paralogs within the same organism ( Figure S5 ), possibly tuning the interaction within the JDP network or allowing for specialized Hsp70-JDP pairs ( Kluck et al., 2002 , Pukszta et al., 2010 , Schlenstedt et al., 1995 , Silberg et al., 1998 ).
Discussion

The structure we present of the J-domain in complex with Hsp70 in the ATP-bound open conformation explains a host of genetic, biochemical, and biophysical data. It confirms previously proposed contacts of the J-domain with Hsp70’s NBD and interdomain linker, reveals previously unsuspected but mechanistically important interactions between the J-domain and the SBDβ of Hsp70, and assigns a functional role for the universally conserved HPD motif of the J-domain and the interdomain linker in Hsp70s. Our structure provides the basis for understanding how JDPs in synergism with substrate proteins stimulate ATP hydrolysis in Hsp70s and thus enables Hsp70s to rapidly trap misfolded proteins.

Since the discovery that the paradigm JDP DnaJ stimulates the ATPase activity of DnaK ( Liberek et al., 1991 ), many attempts have been made to solve the molecular mechanism of this interaction ( Ahmad et al., 2011 , Gässler et al., 1998 , Genevaux et al., 2002 , Greene et al., 1998 , Kumar et al., 2011 , Smock et al., 2010 , Suh et al., 1998 , Suh et al., 1999 ). Residues identified in these studies to be affected by interaction are in close proximity in our structure, and residues found to be functionally important are either at the interface between the J-domain and Hsp70 or on the pathway to the catalytic ATPase center ( Figure 2 ). The most recent attempt to derive a model for the J-domain-Hsp70 interaction used a combination of coarse-grain and atomistic models and evolutionary sequence analysis ( Malinverni et al., 2017 ). The coevolutionary analysis in this study predicted three interaction pairs: Asn187 DnaK -Lys23 JD , Asp208 DnaK -Lys26 JD , and Thr189 DnaK -Arg19 JD . However, these residues do not form contacts in our structure. In fact, they are ∼10, 6, and 16 Å apart from each other, respectively. These residues might be important for initial contacts of the J-domain with DnaK, before attaining the final position. Alternatively, coevolution of these residues may have different reasons. In addition, interactions between His422 DnaK -Glu75 JD and Gln424 DnaK -Lys51 JD were proposed. Glu75 JD is not resolved in our structure. The distance between Gln424 DnaK and Lys51 JD is 14 Å in our structure, precluding interaction. Our mutagenesis data suggest that Lys51 JD is not important for the DnaK-DnaJ interaction. Moreover, a Gln424-to-cysteine replacement had no functional defects in vitro and in vivo and allowed DnaJ and ATP-dependent crosslinking of the protein substrate σ 32 to DnaK using a benzophenone crosslinker specifically attached to this cysteine in position 424 ( Laufen et al., 1999 ). A possible explanation why coevolution analysis failed to reveal the pairs of residues interacting in our structure could be that these residues are highly conserved from bacteria to humans, and the number of deviations may be too small to yield a statistically significant coupling.

It could be argued that by tethering the J-domain to the N terminus of DnaK, a nonphysiological interaction was forced. However, our functional characterization of the fusion construct ( Figure S1 ) and our mutational analysis of DnaK ( Figures 3 and 4 ) and J-domain ( Figure S4 ) single-amino-acid replacement variants strongly argue that our structure represents the physiologically relevant interaction.

Our structure is in conflict with the crystal structure of the J-domain of auxilin in complex with the NBD of bovine Hsc70 ( Jiang et al., 2007 ). Based on a genetic study ( Suh et al., 1998 ), which suggested a direct interaction between Asp35 of DnaJ’s HPD motif and Arg167 in DnaK, Jiang and colleagues replaced Asp876 of the HPD motif in the J-domain of auxilin and Arg171 (corresponding to Arg167 of DnaK) in the NBD of Hsc70 with cysteines and tethered the J-domain to the NBD by a disulfide bridge. However, this structure could not provide a mechanism of J-domain function. As compared to our structure, the J-domain points in a diametrically opposite direction ( Figure S6 ). The only commonality between our structure and the structure of Jiang et al. is the fact that the two residues used to introduce a disulfide bridge indeed interact with each other. However, an aspartate-arginine interaction bridges ∼8 Å between the Cα atoms of the two residues, whereas the distance between the Cα atoms of a disulfide bridge is only ∼5 Å. This might be the reason why steric constraints prevented the J-domain to dock onto its natural docking site. Furthermore, the SBD of the Hsp70 was missing in the previous structure. In our structure, the J-domain interacts with the SBD as well as part of the mechanism of J-domain-substrate synergism, as demonstrated by us. The high conservation of interacting residues ( Figure 5 A) suggests that throughout evolution, J-domains dock onto Hsp70s in a very similar way and that the molecular mechanism of the J-domain-triggered ATP hydrolysis by Hsp70s is conserved as well.

This hypothesis is supported by a mutational study using the J-domain of polyomavirus large T-antigen ( Whalen et al., 2005 ). These authors identified several residues which compromise T antigen function in vivo and stimulation of the ATPase activity of Hsc70 in vitro . In a homology model of polyomavirus J-domain onto the J-domain of DnaJ in our structure and of human Hsc70 on DnaK in our structure, 5 of the 6 identified T-antigen residues would be within interaction distance to Hsc70, requiring only minor adjustments by rotation around single bonds. The remaining amino acid replacements (A33G) in T antigen would be expected to destabilize the J-domain, since in our model, it forms hydrophobic interaction with Leu19 of the J-domain. In addition, Ala33 is in the middle of helix II, and replacement by glycine is expected to break the helix. Thus, our structure is also consistent with a mutagenesis analysis of polyomavirus large T antigen in mammalian cells , suggesting conservation of the mechanistic principal of J-domain-Hsp70 interaction. Moreover, overlaying the J-domain of auxilin on the J-domain of DnaJ and homology modeling human Hsc70 onto DnaK reveals that auxilin could interact with Hsc70 in a way similar to that of the J-domain of DnaJ with DnaK. In fact, mutations used by Jiang and colleagues to support their structure would also affect interaction in such a model. Our single-turnover ATPase data of human Hsc70 in the presence of the human JDP Hdj1 ( Figure 5 ) support our claim that the interaction between the J-domain of DnaJ and DnaK revealed by our structure is evolutionarily conserved.

Our J-domain-DnaK structure allows us to propose a molecular mechanism of how JDPs trigger ATP hydrolysis of Hsp70 chaperones ( Figure 6 ). Hsp70s possess very low basal ATPase activity, because ATP binding rotates the two lobes of the NBD into a position incompatible with γ-phosphate cleavage and SBDβ docking prevents back rotation of the NBD lobes ( Kityk et al., 2012 , Kityk et al., 2015 ). Substrate binding perturbs the NBD-SBDβ interface of Hsp70, releasing the structural constraints of the NBD, as suggested by NMR data ( Zhuravleva et al., 2012 ), but increases the ATPase activity only moderately, since the catalytic residues often bypass the optimal position for hydrolysis due to the high rotational freedom of the NBD lobes. Full stimulation of ATPase activity is achieved in the presence of both substrate and J-domain. The J-domain makes signal transmission from the substrate-binding cleft to the NBD more efficient and thus favors substrate-induced destabilization of the NBD-SBDβ interface and initiation of the back rotation of the NBD lobes ( Figure 6 B). Concomitantly, substrate-induced conformational changes in the SBDβ are transmitted to the J-domain ( Figure S7 ; Movie S1 ), leading through the contacts of the HPD motif to a readjustment of the linker in the NBD crevice, and thereby arrest the NBD lobes and catalytic residues in a position optimal for ATP hydrolysis. In addition, the HPD motif accesses a hydrogen bond network that ends at the catalytic Glu171 DnaK and Lys70 DnaK ( Figure 6 C; Movie S2 ). Thus, the J-domain couples two signals to trigger ATP hydrolysis with concomitant trapping of the substrate. In this way, the Hsp70-JDP machinery achieves ultrahigh affinity, with a non-equilibrium K D that is 2 to 3 orders of magnitude lower than that of the high-affinity ADP-bound equilibrium state ( De Los Rios and Barducci, 2014 ), and the high association rates necessary to efficiently compete with protein aggregation.

    Download : Download high-res image (724KB)
    Download : Download full-size image 

Figure 6 . Model for the Synergistic Stimulation of the ATPase Activity of DnaK by DnaJ and Substrate as Basis for Efficient Trapping of Substrates by Hsp70 Chaperones

(A) After ATP binding, the SBDβ docks onto the rotated lobes of the NBD by interaction between Lys414 and Asp329 and between Asp481 with Arg167 and Ile168, preventing back rotation to an optimal position for ATP hydrolysis . In the absence of substrate and a J-domain, basal ATPase activity is very low (path 1). Mutating Lys414 or Asp481 increases ATPase activity by 25- to 80-fold ( Kityk et al., 2015 ). The addition of substrate (path 2) leads to dissociation of the SBDβ from the NBD through a signal propagated through the SBDβ to the NBD (hatched arrows) ( Zhuravleva et al., 2012 ), stimulating ATPase activity, albeit by only 2- to 5-fold due to complete release of the SBDβ, which allows too much freedom to the lobes of the NBD (green arrows) and dissociation of the linker from the lower crevice (blue arrow). The inefficient stimulation of ATPase activity traps substrates inefficiently (transparent blue substrate symbol on DnaK), and some substrates may dissociate before closure of the substrate-binding pocket (arrow with transparent blue substrate symbol). In the simultaneous presence of DnaJ and a substrate (path 3), the J-domain binds at the interface between SBDβ and NBD, stimulates ATPase activity directly through the interaction network from the linker to the catalytic center and indirectly by making DnaK more sensitive to the substrate signal (solid arrows in the SBDβ), and prevents dissociation of SBDβ and linker, leading to a very high ATPase rate and effective trapping of the substrate.

(B) Structure of the DnaK-J-domain complex highlighting as spheres His33 and Asp35 of the J-domain, residues involved in SBDβ docking onto the NBD, and residues involved in signal transmission from the substrate to the NBD (Val440, Leu484, and Asp148; Kityk et al., 2015 ).

(C) Schematic representation of the network of polar and non-polar contacts connecting the J-domain to the catalytic center of the NBD. Arrows indicate polar contacts, and hatched lines non-polar contacts.

See also Movie S2 .
