Movie S1. Conformational Changes in the SBDβ upon Substrate Binding May Affect the J-Domain Position, Related to Figure 6 . Overlay of the SBDβ of E. coli DnaK with a bound peptide (light red; PDB: 1DKX , Zhu et al., 1996) onto the SBDβ in our structure (dark red). Shown as sticks are residues important for docking the SBDβ onto the NBD (D481, R167, I168, K414, D326; Kityk et al., 2015); residues important for substrate binding (I438, F426) and for signal transmission from the substrate to the NBD (V440, L484, D148; Kityk et al., 2015); residues connecting the J-domain with the SBDβ (D477 DnaK , P419 DnaK , P34 JD , F47 JD , K48 JD ) and interdomain linker of DnaK (H33 JD , R36 JD , K387 DnaK , V389 DnaK , Leu391 DnaK ; hydrophobic contacts between J-domain and linker left away for clarity); and some of the residues transmitting the signal from the J-domain to the catalytic ATPase center (D35 JD , R167 DnaK , Q378 DnaK , R151 DnaK , N170 DnaK , E171 DnaK , K70 DnaK ). The movie toggles between the empty and substrate bound form of the SBDβ and thus illustrates the movement of residues involved in transmitting the signal of the substrate to the NBD and to the J-domain. Dashed black lines are potential polar contacts (distance < 3.5Ε); dashed gray lines are potential hydrophobic interactions (distance <4 Ε). Contacts between the J-domain and the substrate-bound form of the SBDβ are unknown and therefore not shown.
